{
  "doc_id": "34393",
  "text": "Puberty-driven changes of the adrenal and gonadal axes have lasting impacts on brain maturation, including strengthening of neural connections that organize and foster the acquisition of cognitive abilities and social behaviors required for meeting the developmental challenges of adolescence and early adulthood [CITATION_1] . Pubertal changes contribute to the maturation of nerve fibers in the brain's white matter (WM) tracts [CITATION_2] , which connect regions critical for cognitive processing [CITATION_3] . Long-range connectivity of networks supporting emotion regulation and response to stress is modified by the rise of pubertal hormones [CITATION_4] , potentially leading to enduring differences in WM microstructure. In girls, pubertal status (i.e., physical characteristics in relation to peers), timing (i.e., the age at which a given pubertal event has occurred), and tempo (i.e., the speed at which pubertal processes occur) have been associated with subsequent development of disorders involving emotion dysregulation [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] .",
